WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.790 --> 00:00:04.630
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington, D.C.

00:00:23.040 --> 00:00:26.250
&gt;&gt; Ladies and gentlemen, welcome
to the Library of Congress

00:00:26.250 --> 00:00:32.620 position:56%
and to this event -- a conversation
about the novel "Un paese di carta".

00:00:32.620 --> 00:00:36.290
I am Grant Harris, I'm head of
the European Reading Room here

00:00:36.290 --> 00:00:38.740
at the Library of Congress -- not
in this building, the Madison,

00:00:38.740 --> 00:00:41.510
but in the Jefferson
across the street.

00:00:41.510 --> 00:00:45.530
The library is very pleased
to sponsor this event today,

00:00:45.530 --> 00:00:50.940 position:56%
and we do so in partnership with the
library's Italian Language Table,

00:00:50.940 --> 00:00:54.750
and more importantly,
with the Italian Embassy,

00:00:54.750 --> 00:00:59.120
the Italian Cultural Institute,
and especially with the author,

00:00:59.120 --> 00:01:02.880
Dr. Laura Benedetti, from
Georgetown University,

00:01:02.880 --> 00:01:07.980
and reporter Emily Langer
of the "Washington Post".

00:01:07.980 --> 00:01:12.010
The novel we will discuss today
has many interesting facets,

00:01:12.010 --> 00:01:15.160
but let me add one to that.

00:01:15.160 --> 00:01:20.650
The novel refers to an area in
Central Italy called Abruzzo,

00:01:20.650 --> 00:01:25.520
which neighbors the area struck
by the earthquake just a week ago.

00:01:25.520 --> 00:01:29.840
Abruzzo, and in particular,
its major city, L'Aquila,

00:01:29.840 --> 00:01:32.730
from which Dr. Benedetti hails,

00:01:32.730 --> 00:01:38.250
was hit by an equally
devastating earthquake in 2009.

00:01:38.250 --> 00:01:41.520
The Library of Congress is proud
of its Italian collections,

00:01:41.520 --> 00:01:45.480
possibly the largest such
collections outside of Italy.

00:01:45.480 --> 00:01:51.560
Lucia Wolfe, sitting in the front
row, is our specialist for Italy.

00:01:51.560 --> 00:01:55.010
And if you want to research
nearly any aspect of Italy,

00:01:55.010 --> 00:01:58.360
please come back and
talk to Lucia any time.

00:01:58.360 --> 00:02:02.860
In just a minute, I will have
Lucia introduce today's speakers.

00:02:02.860 --> 00:02:06.030
I'll hold the floor for
just another minute here.

00:02:06.030 --> 00:02:09.680
Let me say that we hope you
enjoy the discussion today

00:02:09.680 --> 00:02:12.540
and that you will come back
to use our collections.

00:02:12.540 --> 00:02:16.070
Again, I thank all who have
made this event possible.

00:02:16.070 --> 00:02:20.020
I would now invite to the podium
the library's Italian specialist,

00:02:20.020 --> 00:02:22.320
Lucia Wolfe.

00:02:25.230 --> 00:02:28.490
&gt;&gt; It looks like I'm going
to have to do something here.

00:02:28.490 --> 00:02:29.790
Can you hear me?

00:02:29.790 --> 00:02:31.090
&gt;&gt; Mm-hmm.

00:02:31.090 --> 00:02:35.440
&gt;&gt; OK. So I am Lucia Wolfe and
I'm the reference librarian

00:02:35.440 --> 00:02:39.280
for the Italian collections
at the European division.

00:02:39.280 --> 00:02:41.980
Today's event is a very
special occasion --

00:02:41.980 --> 00:02:45.290
the presentation of Dr. Laura
Benedetti's first novel,

00:02:45.290 --> 00:02:47.170
"Un paese di carta".

00:02:47.170 --> 00:02:50.750
I will leave it to her to
translate the title in English.

00:02:50.750 --> 00:02:55.000
I had something approximately
-- a country of paper --

00:02:55.000 --> 00:02:57.450 position:56%
but it could be a town of paper too.

00:02:57.450 --> 00:03:00.800
But to an American audience,
the most important thing

00:03:00.800 --> 00:03:04.850
for me is the promotion of
Italian culture and language

00:03:04.850 --> 00:03:08.560 position:56%
through our vast Italian collections
at the Library of Congress,

00:03:08.560 --> 00:03:13.440
which I am very proud to say
is close to 400,000 items.

00:03:13.440 --> 00:03:19.720
Although it is impossible to
come up with an exact count.

00:03:19.720 --> 00:03:23.060
The promotion of the
Italian collections is one

00:03:23.060 --> 00:03:26.170
of the most important and
exciting parts of my profession

00:03:26.170 --> 00:03:29.410
because it allows for the
connection between the collections

00:03:29.410 --> 00:03:32.840
and the communities
that the library serves.

00:03:32.840 --> 00:03:38.590 position:56%
As Grant mentioned, the Library of
Congress is one of the few libraries

00:03:38.590 --> 00:03:43.810 position:56%
in the world with the largest number
of Italian items in its collections.

00:03:43.810 --> 00:03:48.340 position:56%
These hundreds of thousands of items
are spread across all divisions

00:03:48.340 --> 00:03:52.590
and come in all formats: prints
and photographs, music scores,

00:03:52.590 --> 00:03:57.410
manuscripts, maps, sound
recordings, motion pictures,

00:03:57.410 --> 00:04:01.390
in addition to the large number
of printed books and periodicals.

00:04:01.390 --> 00:04:07.370
Dr. Benedetti's novel, the
subject of our presentation today,

00:04:07.370 --> 00:04:08.870
is one of the many books written

00:04:08.870 --> 00:04:14.310
by interesting contemporary Italian
authors in our general collections.

00:04:14.310 --> 00:04:16.990
And for the Americans
in our audience,

00:04:16.990 --> 00:04:19.620
I might add that many
English translations

00:04:19.620 --> 00:04:23.800
of Italian authors are also
present in our vast collections.

00:04:23.800 --> 00:04:28.160
The Italian holdings at the
Library of Congress increase

00:04:28.160 --> 00:04:30.920
by the thousands every
year with new items

00:04:30.920 --> 00:04:33.140
from Italy's current
publishing scene,

00:04:33.140 --> 00:04:36.160
of which Dr. Benedetti's
novel is one.

00:04:36.160 --> 00:04:40.640
Personally, I can attest to
this because I have the honor

00:04:40.640 --> 00:04:42.190
to be the person who selects

00:04:42.190 --> 00:04:45.900
and recommends the new
acquisitions from Italy.

00:04:45.900 --> 00:04:49.610
Thank you all for allowing me this
short promotion of the Library

00:04:49.610 --> 00:04:54.060
of Congress' collections to elicit
your interest and patronage.

00:04:54.060 --> 00:04:56.520
Now to our guest speaker.

00:04:56.520 --> 00:05:02.260
Dr. Laura Benedetti holds a laude
summa cum laude from the University

00:05:02.260 --> 00:05:06.780
of Rome-La Sapienza, a master's
from the University of Alberta,

00:05:06.780 --> 00:05:10.260
and Ph.D. from Johns
Hopkins University.

00:05:10.260 --> 00:05:12.410
She taught for eight
years at Harvard

00:05:12.410 --> 00:05:17.490
where she was the John
Loeb Associate Professor

00:05:17.490 --> 00:05:23.980
for the Humanities before
joining Georgetown in 2002.

00:05:23.980 --> 00:05:27.800
Her publications include
"La sconfitta di Diana.

00:05:27.800 --> 00:05:33.030 position:56%
Un percorso per la Gerusalemme
liberata", "The Tigress in the Snow:

00:05:33.030 --> 00:05:38.010
Motherhood and Literature in
20th-Century Italy", the addition

00:05:38.010 --> 00:05:43.000
and translation of one of
Italy's earliest women writers,

00:05:43.000 --> 00:05:47.350
Lucrezia Marinella, "Esortazioni
alle donne e agli altri",

00:05:47.350 --> 00:05:50.960
and most recently,
"Un paese di carta".

00:05:50.960 --> 00:05:54.830
Incidentally, all of these
books by Dr. Benedetti are

00:05:54.830 --> 00:05:57.110
in the library's collections.

00:05:57.110 --> 00:06:00.000
She has been the guest of
honor at annual meetings

00:06:00.000 --> 00:06:02.980
of the American Association
of Italian Studies as well

00:06:02.980 --> 00:06:07.790
as the recipient of various awards:
the Flaiano International Prize

00:06:07.790 --> 00:06:12.740 position:56%
for Italian Studies, the Wise Woman
Award from the National Organization

00:06:12.740 --> 00:06:15.570
of Italian-American
Women, and the gold medal

00:06:15.570 --> 00:06:22.000
from the Federazione Associazioni
Abruzzesi U.S.A. She is currently

00:06:22.000 --> 00:06:25.510
associate editor and book review
editor of Italian Culture:

00:06:25.510 --> 00:06:28.780
The Journal of the American
Association of Italian Studies.

00:06:28.780 --> 00:06:33.370
Our next guest speaker is Emily
Langer, a reporter with the

00:06:33.370 --> 00:06:37.220
"Washington Post" where she works
on the obituaries desk and says

00:06:37.220 --> 00:06:41.660
about her work, "Every day I
have the opportunity to delve

00:06:41.660 --> 00:06:45.380
into a different life:
a writer, a scientist,

00:06:45.380 --> 00:06:48.210
an artist, a doctor, and so on."

00:06:48.210 --> 00:06:50.880
She also writes occasionally
feature stories

00:06:50.880 --> 00:06:53.850
for the newspaper including
two articles about a pair

00:06:53.850 --> 00:06:59.140
of Italian sisters who survived
the Holocaust as very young girls.

00:06:59.140 --> 00:07:01.900
Finally, she is a graduate
of the Italian Department

00:07:01.900 --> 00:07:03.400
at Georgetown University.

00:07:03.400 --> 00:07:08.570
And in 2010-2011 was a Fulbright
fellow in Trieste, Italy.

00:07:08.570 --> 00:07:12.030
And now, I will leave
you to our presentation.

00:07:12.030 --> 00:07:14.510
Thank you all.

00:07:14.510 --> 00:07:18.040
[ Applause ]

00:07:18.040 --> 00:07:20.380
So thank you so much, all
of you, for being here.

00:07:20.380 --> 00:07:23.350
Thank you to Lucia and
to Grant for having us.

00:07:23.350 --> 00:07:27.600
But most of all, thank you, Laura,
for writing this magnificent book.

00:07:27.600 --> 00:07:29.950
I was Laura's student 14 years ago

00:07:29.950 --> 00:07:32.500
at the Italian Department
of Georgetown.

00:07:32.500 --> 00:07:36.260
And it was my first day at
Georgetown and her first day

00:07:36.260 --> 00:07:41.080
at Georgetown, and I stumbled into
her class about the Italian writer,

00:07:41.080 --> 00:07:44.550
Italo Calvino, who by the
way, figures in this novel,

00:07:44.550 --> 00:07:46.940
and I've been hanging
around ever since.

00:07:46.940 --> 00:07:50.800
So I'm very glad to be
here with her today.

00:07:50.800 --> 00:07:54.510
So as Grant said, Laura
is from L'Aquila,

00:07:54.510 --> 00:07:58.990
which you probably remember was hit
by a terrible earthquake in 2009.

00:07:58.990 --> 00:08:02.470
And I wanted to ask you
first, given what you know

00:08:02.470 --> 00:08:05.480
about L'Aquila's experience,
what does Amatrice face

00:08:05.480 --> 00:08:08.060
in the next number
of years recovering

00:08:08.060 --> 00:08:11.650
from the earthquake last week?

00:08:11.650 --> 00:08:17.220
&gt;&gt; Well, first of all, L'Aquila
is only 30 miles from Amatrice,

00:08:17.220 --> 00:08:22.590
so the quake brought back
some very sad memories

00:08:22.590 --> 00:08:26.560
and also created some new
damage in L'Aquila as well.

00:08:26.560 --> 00:08:29.480
As far as Amatrice is concerned,

00:08:29.480 --> 00:08:33.720
of course there the devastation
is terrible, but I hear,

00:08:33.720 --> 00:08:36.100
there's strong determination
from the people

00:08:36.100 --> 00:08:40.010
of Amatrice to rebuild their town.

00:08:40.010 --> 00:08:41.980
And now I also hear
from the government

00:08:41.980 --> 00:08:45.920
that the model was
followed for L'Aquila,

00:08:45.920 --> 00:08:50.530
so the idea of closing off the
town and building somewhere else,

00:08:50.530 --> 00:08:53.730
is not a model to be
followed in this case.

00:08:53.730 --> 00:08:57.660
And this is very reassuring to
me, so I hope that in a way,

00:08:57.660 --> 00:09:00.690
the experience -- the
tragic experience

00:09:00.690 --> 00:09:04.920
of the L'Aquila earthquake will
help the people in Amatrice

00:09:04.920 --> 00:09:08.840
to rebuild faster and better homes.

00:09:08.840 --> 00:09:16.260
And incidentally, Amatrice was part
of L'Aquila territory until 1927.

00:09:16.260 --> 00:09:19.450
There is a very powerful link
between the two communities.

00:09:19.450 --> 00:09:24.550
And in fact, I just read in the
paper today that several families

00:09:24.550 --> 00:09:28.200
from Amatrice just arrived in
L'Aquila and will be housed

00:09:28.200 --> 00:09:33.160
in the houses that were built
after the earthquake in L'Aquila.

00:09:33.160 --> 00:09:36.820
So there is a very strong link
between the two communities.

00:09:36.820 --> 00:09:41.120
&gt;&gt; What is the situation in
L'Aquila today, six years --

00:09:41.120 --> 00:09:42.830
seven years after the earthquake?

00:09:42.830 --> 00:09:50.560
&gt;&gt; Well, in the past two
years let's say, since 2014,

00:09:50.560 --> 00:09:52.100
things have really changed.

00:09:52.100 --> 00:09:56.950
And the rebuilding of the town has
had a very powerful acceleration.

00:09:56.950 --> 00:10:00.050
So actually, I'm cautiously
optimistic about the --

00:10:00.050 --> 00:10:01.470
-- of the town.

00:10:01.470 --> 00:10:04.720
There are several question
marks, especially in terms

00:10:04.720 --> 00:10:07.830
of what the population
is going to do,

00:10:07.830 --> 00:10:10.240
because many people have
left L'Aquila, many people,

00:10:10.240 --> 00:10:13.980
especially after what happened
in Amatrice, don't feel safe

00:10:13.980 --> 00:10:21.950
in the center of town, so there are
still many issues to be discussed

00:10:21.950 --> 00:10:24.070
and many problems to be solved.

00:10:24.070 --> 00:10:25.450
But I'm cautiously optimistic.

00:10:25.450 --> 00:10:29.580
&gt;&gt; I was talking to a friend
after the earthquake last week,

00:10:29.580 --> 00:10:32.030
and what he said was that
in the United States,

00:10:32.030 --> 00:10:35.390
we tend to think Italy for its
beauty and for its history,

00:10:35.390 --> 00:10:40.450
and that what these earthquakes
have exposed is also its fragility.

00:10:40.450 --> 00:10:44.220
And I wanted to ask you about the
title of your novel, as they said,

00:10:44.220 --> 00:10:47.360
"Un paese di carta",
which relates to this,

00:10:47.360 --> 00:10:51.810
what did you mean with your title?

00:10:51.810 --> 00:10:54.590
&gt;&gt; First of all, thank
you, Lucia, and thank you,

00:10:54.590 --> 00:10:56.330
Grant, and thank you, Emily.

00:10:56.330 --> 00:10:57.630
This is [inaudible].

00:10:57.630 --> 00:10:59.530
Thank you all for being here.

00:10:59.530 --> 00:11:06.000 position:56%
But it's very interesting that Lucia
immediately brought up the issue

00:11:06.000 --> 00:11:10.900 position:56%
of the title, because the title is
very hard to translate into English.

00:11:10.900 --> 00:11:13.170
And it turned out to
be more ambiguous

00:11:13.170 --> 00:11:15.920
than I thought even in Italian.

00:11:15.920 --> 00:11:20.120
In my mind -- in the
mind of the artist --

00:11:20.120 --> 00:11:23.930
the title meant Italy
as a cultural --

00:11:23.930 --> 00:11:26.220
and especially literary
construction --

00:11:26.220 --> 00:11:33.400
as opposed to Italy as a
political and physical entity.

00:11:33.400 --> 00:11:38.930 position:56%
So in other words, one of the
protagonists of the novel is a woman

00:11:38.930 --> 00:11:45.060
who left Italy at the end of the
50s and has the rest of her life

00:11:45.060 --> 00:11:50.680 position:56%
in the United States, but has a kept
very strong relationship with Italy.

00:11:50.680 --> 00:11:55.640
But Italy -- the Italy that she
loves is un paese di carta --

00:11:55.640 --> 00:12:01.360
it's a country made of paper in
the sense that it lives in books --

00:12:01.360 --> 00:12:03.640
lives in its cultural artifacts.

00:12:03.640 --> 00:12:08.400
It's not Italy as a
political entity.

00:12:08.400 --> 00:12:11.270
There is only one passage
in the novel

00:12:11.270 --> 00:12:19.140
where this expression is mentioned,
and it is precisely when Alice --

00:12:19.140 --> 00:12:21.530
so the oldest of the three women --

00:12:21.530 --> 00:12:25.460
the novel is about three
women, the oldest one is Alice.

00:12:25.460 --> 00:12:30.380
And Alice is writing a letter to
her fiancé in Italy explaining

00:12:30.380 --> 00:12:32.290
that she'll never go back.

00:12:32.290 --> 00:12:36.320
And she says, "But
that does not matter

00:12:36.320 --> 00:12:40.610
because I will always
inhabit the Italy I love --

00:12:40.610 --> 00:12:43.790
a country made of paper."

00:12:43.790 --> 00:12:47.150
But when I presented the
book, because I had the chance

00:12:47.150 --> 00:12:51.170
to present the book all over
during the past year from Naples

00:12:51.170 --> 00:12:53.180
to Venice and Turin, you know.

00:12:53.180 --> 00:12:57.500
And when I presented it in
L'Aquila, especially I presented it

00:12:57.500 --> 00:13:02.750
in several schools in L'Aquila,
and when I asked about the meaning

00:13:02.750 --> 00:13:09.570
of the title, the answer I got
the most often was it's a fragile

00:13:09.570 --> 00:13:14.460
country, it's a vulnerable
country, it's a country

00:13:14.460 --> 00:13:18.540
that seems very solid, but
could collapse at any minute.

00:13:18.540 --> 00:13:23.740
And I think there is really an
interference of the experience

00:13:23.740 --> 00:13:29.890
of the earthquake which
taught us that -- fragility.

00:13:29.890 --> 00:13:33.420
But it's very interesting
to me that now

00:13:33.420 --> 00:13:38.660
for the first time yesterday
actually, when we posted something

00:13:38.660 --> 00:13:44.290 position:56%
on Facebook, I also -- since this is
the first presentation of the novel

00:13:44.290 --> 00:13:50.230
in English -- so I commented on
Emily's post and I said, "Yes,

00:13:50.230 --> 00:13:52.350
this is the first presentation
in English which brings

00:13:52.350 --> 00:13:55.810
up the issue how to
translate the title."

00:13:55.810 --> 00:13:59.020
And actually, somebody
answered in private,

00:13:59.020 --> 00:14:03.390
because we're mostly Italians
answer, and one of them said,

00:14:03.390 --> 00:14:08.320
"You know, forget about un paese
di carta altogether and focus

00:14:08.320 --> 00:14:12.310
on something like she's
back -- she's back home."

00:14:12.310 --> 00:14:14.000
And so I was thinking
that going home,

00:14:14.000 --> 00:14:17.950
although it's completely different,
couldn't be a possible title.

00:14:17.950 --> 00:14:23.620 position:56%
But anyway, the title is -- yeah,
it was central in my way of thinking

00:14:23.620 --> 00:14:25.520
about the book when
I started writing it,

00:14:25.520 --> 00:14:28.680
so it's a challenging title.

00:14:28.680 --> 00:14:31.480
&gt;&gt; So you mentioned that the
book is about three women.

00:14:31.480 --> 00:14:36.300
So Alice is the oldest, then
Alice's daughter is Jane,

00:14:36.300 --> 00:14:39.110
and Jane's daughter is Sarah.

00:14:39.110 --> 00:14:41.120
So Sarah is Alice's granddaughter.

00:14:41.120 --> 00:14:46.320
And three generations of
women over more than 50 years

00:14:46.320 --> 00:14:49.900
from World War II all the
way up until the aftermath

00:14:49.900 --> 00:14:52.200
of the earthquake in L'Aquila.

00:14:52.200 --> 00:14:54.470
So the first character
we meet is Sarah.

00:14:54.470 --> 00:14:56.040
Tell us about Sarah.

00:14:56.040 --> 00:14:58.310
&gt;&gt; Yeah. It's hard
to talk about Sarah

00:14:58.310 --> 00:15:00.320 position:56%
without talking about the other two.

00:15:00.320 --> 00:15:05.790
So the oldest one is the only
one who has a clear birthdate

00:15:05.790 --> 00:15:10.140
and also a death date
in the novel, is Alice.

00:15:10.140 --> 00:15:17.340
Alice was born in 1930 in L'Aquila
and dies in Bethesda in 2010.

00:15:17.340 --> 00:15:23.360
She left Italy in 1957 and
she had a daughter, Jane.

00:15:23.360 --> 00:15:27.450 position:56%
Jane in turn had three children, but
especially had this one daughter,

00:15:27.450 --> 00:15:32.170
Sarah, who is 18 when
the novel begins in 2010.

00:15:32.170 --> 00:15:38.970
She's multilingual, very bright,
very sensitive, and little bit

00:15:38.970 --> 00:15:41.420
of a mess when the novel begins.

00:15:41.420 --> 00:15:46.690
So the novel, in a way, is
also the [inaudible] of Sarah,

00:15:46.690 --> 00:15:48.650
so it's a novel of formation.

00:15:48.650 --> 00:15:54.100
A young protagonist manages
to overcome the challenges

00:15:54.100 --> 00:15:56.820
on her path and enter adulthood.

00:15:56.820 --> 00:16:00.730
To a certain extent, because
I'm a little skeptical

00:16:00.730 --> 00:16:04.800
about drastic resolutions, but the
Sarah, at the end of the novel,

00:16:04.800 --> 00:16:09.070
is much stronger than the
Sarah we meet at the beginning.

00:16:09.070 --> 00:16:14.640
One more thing about Sarah, Sarah
was born when her mother, Jane,

00:16:14.640 --> 00:16:20.060
thought she had enough of
raising children and was ready

00:16:20.060 --> 00:16:23.560
to start her career as a lawyer.

00:16:23.560 --> 00:16:30.580
So Jane even considered
having an abortion.

00:16:30.580 --> 00:16:35.270
In the end, she did
have this child, Sarah,

