00:40:27.240 --> 00:40:32.160
So you referred to Alberto who is
Alice's brother, and the Germans,

00:40:32.160 --> 00:40:35.990
and he's going off
with a hunting rifle.

00:40:35.990 --> 00:40:37.790
This refers to the war, of course.

00:40:37.790 --> 00:40:43.070
What was happening in L'Aquila
during the war at this time,

00:40:43.070 --> 00:40:47.740
just give some background.

00:40:47.740 --> 00:40:50.190
&gt;&gt; Yeah. Well L'Aquila -- I mean,

00:40:50.190 --> 00:40:53.390
I don't want to give a
little history class, sorry.

00:40:53.390 --> 00:40:56.890
But just very briefly
to introduce Alberto.

00:40:56.890 --> 00:41:04.270
L'Aquila all of a sudden found
itself at the center of action

00:41:04.270 --> 00:41:08.320
in a way because now talking 1943.

00:41:08.320 --> 00:41:17.650
Mussolini had resigned on July 25,
1943, and had been made prisoner.

00:41:17.650 --> 00:41:21.840
So he had been put in a prison
nearly L'Aquila in the mountains,

00:41:21.840 --> 00:41:25.030
in the Apennines on the Gran Sasso.

00:41:25.030 --> 00:41:29.830
Then September 8th, Italy signs
the armistice with the allies.

00:41:29.830 --> 00:41:34.180
September 12th, the
Germans free Mussolini

00:41:34.180 --> 00:41:38.170
from his prison in the Apennines.

00:41:38.170 --> 00:41:41.720
So the events were really
going very, very fast.

00:41:41.720 --> 00:41:43.800
Everybody was very confused.

00:41:43.800 --> 00:41:49.380 position:56%
The king had flown to the south, the
allies were coming from the south.

00:41:49.380 --> 00:41:53.480
All of a sudden, L'Aquila
was packed with Germans.

00:41:53.480 --> 00:42:00.310 position:56%
And there had been this announcement
that all young men between age 18

00:42:00.310 --> 00:42:04.570
and 25 had to be registered.

00:42:04.570 --> 00:42:08.560
So people were afraid of
that to mean, you know,

00:42:08.560 --> 00:42:11.780
that could mean a deportation,
that could mean being forced

00:42:11.780 --> 00:42:17.430
to fight alongside with the
Germans and so on and so forth.

00:42:17.430 --> 00:42:21.330
So in this very confusing
atmosphere, there were a group

00:42:21.330 --> 00:42:28.110
of young people from L'Aquila who
on September 22nd left the town

00:42:28.110 --> 00:42:34.660
and went to the mountains probably
to start a partisan brigade

00:42:34.660 --> 00:42:41.220
or to reach other groups of
partisans in the mountains.

00:42:41.220 --> 00:42:43.340
They were immediately captured.

00:42:43.340 --> 00:42:44.720
They were captured the day after.

00:42:44.720 --> 00:42:47.320
They were brought back to town,

00:42:47.320 --> 00:42:51.860
and nine of them were
killed -- were executed.

00:42:51.860 --> 00:43:00.810 position:56%
So this was perhaps one of the first
episodes of resistance in Italy

00:43:00.810 --> 00:43:05.750
because again, you know, the
armistice was on September 8th,

00:43:05.750 --> 00:43:10.400
they were killed on September 23rd.

00:43:10.400 --> 00:43:15.390
There is a lot of mystery
surrounding this episode

00:43:15.390 --> 00:43:20.940 position:56%
because the news of that was kept as
a secret until the end of the war,

00:43:20.940 --> 00:43:27.510
until L'Aquila was liberated,
which happened on June 13, 1944,

00:43:27.510 --> 00:43:31.320
so almost ten months later.

00:43:31.320 --> 00:43:34.350 position:56%
And it is still a mystery because --

00:43:34.350 --> 00:43:36.670
and I did not know this
when I wrote the book,

00:43:36.670 --> 00:43:41.060
I found out about this later --

00:43:41.060 --> 00:43:45.580
there was a trial after
the war in 1947,

00:43:45.580 --> 00:43:48.530
there was a trial about
this episode.

00:43:48.530 --> 00:43:53.980
But the proceedings of the trial
are kept secret for 70 years.

00:43:53.980 --> 00:43:58.530
So the trial was in 1947,
now next year in 2017,

00:43:58.530 --> 00:44:03.450
we'll finally know what was
established during that trial.

00:44:03.450 --> 00:44:06.650
Italy does not have the [inaudible]
of Freedom of Information Act.

00:44:06.650 --> 00:44:11.190
So they have this --
the judge can say --

00:44:11.190 --> 00:44:17.720
can establish that the
proceedings can be kept secret

00:44:17.720 --> 00:44:19.930
and cannot divulged to the public.

00:44:19.930 --> 00:44:24.390
I know that a journalist
tried to have access --

00:44:24.390 --> 00:44:28.680
petition to have access to the
proceedings, and he was unable to.

00:44:28.680 --> 00:44:31.370
I know of this case because the
journalist published an article

00:44:31.370 --> 00:44:32.670
about this.

00:44:32.670 --> 00:44:34.590
I don't know how many other
people tried to find out more

00:44:34.590 --> 00:44:41.140
about the trial and they were
prohibited from doing so.

00:44:41.140 --> 00:44:51.480
The link with the novel is that
I imagine that Alberto was one

00:44:51.480 --> 00:44:57.870
of the nine martyrs -- as they are
called in Italian, [inaudible] --

00:44:57.870 --> 00:45:01.870 position:56%
who was killed in this circumstance.

00:45:01.870 --> 00:45:06.550
So it's an imaginary character,
but he combines the characteristics

00:45:06.550 --> 00:45:13.840
